<p>President Trump has announced that he intends to grant a full presidential pardon to former Honduran president Juan Orlando Hernández, who is serving a lengthy U.S. prison sentence after being convicted in 2024 in a New York federal court on drug trafficking and weapons charges. Trump wrote on social media that, based on people he &quot;greatly respect&quot;,</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/moBzSV5VNpt3Gsx2mDGLXxXrLdxiN6QyXtQFOC-67I0c2RbxT1p28QU8i3IfEK1mWv-1yjdrflGukiLD5SSFco1I2aWNlhBh26nn0sxrFZVhJERSrLzgYptVumec9-xYWAkEiGabYqqxjW3TbXj8w18AFs3TGeLqacE-Vps98MJpjlhRw3XJvZU' alt='Juan Orlando Hernández, then president of Honduras, addressing the United Nations in 2019.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Hernández sentence: The New York court imposed a 45-year prison term on Hernández after finding that he worked with cocaine traffickers who moved large quantities of drugs toward the United States and accepted substantial bribes for political protection.</li><li>Extradition history: Hernández was arrested in Honduras after leaving office, then extradited to the United States where he faced trial on charges that he had effectively turned Honduras into a so‑called narco-state during his years in power.</li><li>Honduran elections: Trump’s announcement comes just days before Hondurans vote in a presidential election in which Nasry Asfura, the candidate from Hernández’s National Party, is contesting the country’s leadership.</li><li>Trump’s reasoning: In his Truth Social post, Trump said that, according to people he respects, Hernández had been treated &quot;very harshly and unfairly,&quot; presenting this as his main justification for the decision.</li><li>Drug policy contrast: The planned pardon comes even as Trump continues to speak publicly about being tough on drug trafficking and illegal narcotics entering the United States, a stance that has been central to his broader security messaging.</li></ul><blockquote>I will be granting a Full and Complete Pardon to Former President Juan Orlando Hernandez who has been, according to many people that I greatly respect, treated very harshly and unfairly - President Donald Trump</blockquote><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>President Trump: Trump framed the decision as correcting what he called very harsh and unfair treatment of Hernández, citing people he said he greatly respects as influencing his view that clemency is warranted. (<a href='https://www.scmp.com/news/world/americas/article/3334592/trump-says-hell-pardon-ex-honduras-president-serving-us-prison-sentence'>South China Morning Post</a>)</li><li>U.S. prosecutors: At trial, American prosecutors argued that Hernández turned Honduras into a platform for large-scale cocaine trafficking toward the United States by protecting traffickers in exchange for millions of dollars. (<a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2025/11/28/world/americas/trump-pardon-honduras-hernandez.html'>The New York Times</a>)</li><li>Hernández’s family: After Trump’s announcement, Hernández’s wife Ana García publicly welcomed the news alongside their daughters in Tegucigalpa, presenting the pardon plan as a step toward justice for her husband. (<a href='https://www.lemonde.fr/en/international/article/2025/11/29/trump-says-he-plans-to-pardon-former-honduran-president-for-drug-trafficking-sentence_6747951_4.html'>Le Monde</a>)</li><li>Honduran opposition voices: Opponents of Hernández in Honduras have long argued that his conviction validated years of domestic accusations that his administration was intertwined with drug cartels and abusive security forces. (<a href='https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2025/11/28/trump-says-will-pardon-former-honduras-leader-before-presidential-vote'>Al Jazeera</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.reddit.com/r/inthenews/comments/1p9bby7/trump_plans_to_pardon_former_honduran_president/'>Trump plans to pardon former Honduran President Juan Orlando Hernandez, convicted last year in a U.S. court of conspiring to imp